Kith’s Monday Program for Fall/Winter 2025 unites sports legacy with elevated streetwear, reimagining New York Yankees iconography through a luxury lens. Known for blending athletic culture with contemporary design, this collection taps into nostalgia while projecting a bold new vision of modern style.

From custom baseball bats engraved with heritage motifs to premium gloves and lifestyle-ready apparel, every piece channels the Yankees’ timeless identity with Kith’s meticulous craftsmanship. The palette leans into clean neutrals, textured woods, and signature navy accents, symbols of both tradition and urban edge.

This drop isn’t just about sportswear; it’s about cultural storytelling. Kith celebrates the energy of the Yankees, not only as a team but as a global symbol of New York resilience and style. The Monday Program serves both collectors and everyday wearers who crave authenticity, quality, and heritage redefined for today.

Available September 22, 2025, a moment where baseball history collides with streetwear’s sharpest expression.

Nearly three decades later, the America’s Cup remains one of the rare sneakers that brings sports, luxury, and streetwear together.

adidas Y-3 Gendo Superstar (Black, Size 10.5)

When Yohji Yamamoto first partnered with adidas in 2002 to launch Y-3, it redefined how sportswear and high fashion could intersect. Two decades later, the Gendo Superstar pushed that vision into radical new territory.

Unveiled during Paris Fashion Week in 2022, the Gendo transformed the iconic adidas Superstar into a piece of wearable architecture. The shoe retained its leather upper and shell-toe heritage, but sat atop a hollowed-out, sculptural plate designed to “elevate” the wearer — literally and conceptually. Its open-arch platform blurred the line between sneaker and object, a bold experiment that drew coverage from Highsnobiety, Hypebeast, and Vogue, with headlines framing it as one of the most daring sneaker designs of the year.

The Gendo Superstar wasn’t made for mass wear. Its limited release, avant-garde silhouette, and high price point made it instantly polarizing — celebrated by collectors of Yohji Yamamoto’s work and fashion-forward sneakerheads, while bewildering traditionalists. Today, it stands as one of the most striking examples of Y-3’s philosophy: challenging expectations while preserving the DNA of adidas’ most iconic sneaker.
